        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Chinese charm offensive fails</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/ursula-von-der-leyen-li-qiang-eu-china-meeting.png" alt="Commission chief Ursula von der Leyen and Chinese Premier Li Qiang" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Commission chief Ursula von der Leyen and Chinese Premier Li Qiang. Credits: X/ von der Leyen official profile</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">China’s recent efforts to <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-h2-2-strengthen-ties-with-europe" target="_blank">strengthen ties with Europe</a> have fallen short of expectations. Even after highlighting European brands at its consumer expo in Hainan, Beijing’s attempt to woo the EU has not achieved much in easing concerns about trade imbalances and overcapacity. Chinese state media have highlighted warmth and openness, but most EU leaders remain cautious and critical.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Ursula Von der Leyen emphasized the importance of fair trade in a conversation with Premier Li Qiang, but was critical of China for enabling trade diversion and global overcapacity. Additionally, she pressed China on market entry and its passive stance on Russia’s war in Ukraine. The EU, among other trading groups, fears that Chinese exports barred from the US will flow into alternative markets, triggering trade wars.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          As China seeks to capitalize on US-EU tensions, Brussels aims to protect its economic interests. Despite appearances of harmony, the divide over structural issues runs deep. Despite the EU having a standard <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-h2-3-policy-towards-china" target="_blank">policy towards China</a>, different members of the EU bloc also have differing stances on China.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section css-class="mj_section" background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">China flipflop</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;"><strong>Summary: Trump states that tariffs on China will be reduced, but the exact amount has not been specified yet. </strong></p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          President Trump may <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-h3-4-change-his-approach" target="_blank">change his approach</a> in the trade war with China. He suggested that tariffs on Chinese goods could "come down substantially," but not to zero. This marks a shift from his recent aggressive stance, where tariffs exceeded 145%.
        </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          His comments follow Treasury Secretary Scott Bessent's suggestion that the trade war is unsustainable and that he expects a de-escalation of the trade war. He said the goal should be to rebalance trade, not completely decouple. China's Foreign Ministry urged the US to respond fairly and respectfully. Even with Trump’s softer tone, Beijing remains firm and stands its ground. They retaliated with tariffs and restrictions on American firms.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Trump's hopeful outlook for negotiations contrasts with China's aggravation. President Xi has spent the last week exploring alternative diplomatic routes in Southeast Asia. He expressed a desire for an agreement, saying the US would “be very nice” to China. However, tensions persist as both sides are on edge, planning their next moves.</p>
        </mj-text>
