          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>🇸🇾 Syria arrests two Palestinian militant group leaders</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Two senior officials from Palestinian Islamic Jihad (PIJ) <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-br1-5-were-arrested" target="_blank">were arrested</a> in Syria “without explanation.” The group expressed disappointment over these detentions, which have relied on Syrian support for years. These arrests come as Syria’s political landscape shifts after the December overthrow of Bashar al-Assad’s regime by militants led by Hayat Tahrir al-Sham (HTS). 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Interim President al-Sharaa is working to stabilize the country while seeking relief from US sanctions. The US reportedly pressured Damascus to limit support for Palestinian militants and reduce Iranian influence. Experts say targeting PIJ is a strategic move as Iran backs them. Syria faces the challenge of meeting Washington’s demands while balancing its monetary needs and avoiding the appearance of being too subservient to Western powers.</p>
        </mj-text>
