          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Why is Kashmir so contested?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/kashmir-region-dispute-map-india-pakistan-china.png" alt="Map showing the contested Kashmir region and its territorial divisions administered by India, Pakistan, and China" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>
          Map showing the contested Kashmir region and its territorial divisions administered by India, Pakistan, and China. Credits: Britannica</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">    
           Kashmir has been a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-f1-7-contested-region" target="_blank">contested region</a> since the partition of India in 1947. The ruler, Maharaja Hari Singh, was Hindu, but most of his population was Muslim. During the partition, the princely states were given the option to join India or Pakistan. Initially, he didn’t want to be part of either. It wasn’t until Pakistani tribesmen invaded Kashmir in October 1947 that he turned to India for help. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          On the advice of India's governor-general, Lord Mountbatten, the Maharaja signed the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-f1-8-instrument-of-accession" target="_blank">Instrument of Accession</a>, ceding control over foreign and defence policy to India. While Pakistan cites numerous UN resolutions in favour of a UN-run referendum to decide the future of Kashmir, India says the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-24-04-2025-simla-agreement-1972" target="_blank">Simla Agreement of 1972</a> binds the two countries to solve this on a state-to-state basis.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Amid this, Kashmiri nationalism saw a rise as the Jammu Kashmir Liberation Front was founded with the hope of making an independent state through the reunification of Indian-administered and Pakistan-administered Kashmir.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Kashmir faced wars, insurgencies, and diplomatic deadlocks throughout the 20th century. Tensions grew due to military stand-offs, terrorist activity, and conflicting visions for the region's future. Insurgencies and terrorist groups have regrouped since the 2015 elections in India's Kashmir. The ruling BJP party became a more significant player in the region when it formed part of a coalition government with the regional Muslim People's Democratic Party.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          A handful of elements keep it prone to terrorism and conflict. It is sandwiched between three major nuclear powers: India, China, and Pakistan. Competing narratives, grievances, and visions for the area exist. Finding a resolution to please all parties is an uphill battle. </p>
        </mj-text>
